{"aid": "40211667", "title": "Leicestershire community fridge saves tonnes of food from tip", "url": "https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cn3d18v70n2o", "domain": "bbc.com", "votes": 1, "user": "whereistimbo", "posted_at": "2024-04-30 14:55:27", "comments": 0, "source_title": "Leicestershire community fridge saves tonnes of food from tip", "source_text": "Leicestershire community fridge saves tonnes of food from tip\n\n# Community fridge saving tonnes of food from landfill\n\n11 hours ago\n\nJo Hollis,BBC Radio Leicester\n\nAndrew Carpenter\n\nThe community fridge offers fresh fruit and vegetables as well as other\npackaged food\n\nA community fridge in Leicestershire has saved almost eight tonnes of food\nfrom going to landfill since it opened 18 months ago, organisers have said.\n\nThe Village Community Fridge in St Mary's Road, Market Harborough, opened in\nNovember 2022 to reduce waste.\n\nOrganisers of the non-profit project say they have seen a rise in the number\nof people using the service and some are in food poverty.\n\nThe surplus food is donated by shops, businesses and individuals from the\narea.\n\nThe initiative, which is available to anyone, offers fresh fruit and\nvegetables as well as other packaged food from Tuesday to Saturday.\n\nKim Oldfield, who runs the project, said it started with one fridge and had\nsince doubled in size, with twice the amount of pantry space for produce.\n\nShe said the hub had saved 7.7 tonnes of food from being thrown away since it\nopened.\n\n\"Only last week in just one day we were given 80 kilos (176lbs) of food that\nwould have just gone straight in the bin from only two supermarkets,\" she\nsaid.\n\nAndrew Carpenter\n\nOrganiser Kim Oldfield says they are stopping tonnes of good food being wasted\n\nMs Oldfield said the project was currently run by 10 volunteers and needed\nmore people to help to collect donations and arrange produce.\n\n\"We're delighted to be able to offer free food, but cannot do it without your\nhelp,\" she added.\n\n\"We rely heavily on donations and volunteer support.\"\n\nShe said people could donate excess produce from their allotments, or\nvegetables grown in their gardens.\n\nThe community fridge is part of a national network of 600 across the country,\nco-ordinated and part -funded by environmental charity Hubbub.\n\nFollow BBC Leicester on Facebook, on X, or on Instagram. Send your story ideas\nto eastmidsnews@bbc.co.uk or via WhatsApp on 0808 100 2210.\n\n## Harborough Community Fridge\n\n## Community Fridge UK\n\nMarket Harborough\n\nFood\n\nRelated\n\n## Visiting times extended at Leicestershire hospitals\n\n7 days ago\n\nLeicester\n\n## Council reviews CCTV use over China government links\n\n18 Apr 2024\n\nLeicester\n\n## Disruption warning ahead of major weekend rail work\n\n17 Apr 2024\n\nLeicester\n\nMore\n\n2 hrs ago\n\n## 'Brexit trade checks will cost me \u00a3200,000 a year'\n\nFirms warn of higher costs but the government says its new border model will\nimprove biosecurity.\n\n2 hrs ago\n\nBusiness\n\n1 day ago\n\n## Bread and biscuit prices could rise due to wet weather\n\nPoor wheat crops mean food producers may have to import ingredients,\npotentially increasing costs.\n\n1 day ago\n\nBusiness\n\n1 day ago\n\n## A visit to the first Arab-majority city in the US\n\nLocated just outside Detroit, Dearborn offers travellers a unique chance to\neat their way through the Middle East while exploring how Arab Americans have\nshaped the nation.\n\n1 day ago\n\nTravel\n\n2 days ago\n\n## An insider's guide to the best sushi in Tokyo\n\nJapanese food author, reviewer and guide Yukari Sakamoto shares her picks of\nthe five best sushi restaurants in the Japanese capital.\n\n2 days ago\n\nTravel\n\n7 days ago\n\n## Marmalade-maker wins international competition\n\nStephen Snead's marmalade-making began in 2017 - now he has won two global\nawards for his creations.\n\n7 days ago\n\nHereford & Worcester\n\nCopyright 2024 BBC. All rights reserved. The